 the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert Pigot was born about 1140. She married Robert Pichot about 1161, in Butley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1140–":"umbes 1140–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","about 1162":"umbes 1162","Abt 1140":"umbes 1140","Abt 1161":"umbes 1161","before 1162":"enne 1162","1162":"1162","1140":"1140","of Butley, Cheshire, England":"Butley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"Abt 1140–":"noin 1140–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1162–Male":"1162–Kuollut","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","about 1162":"noin 1162","Abt 1140":"noin 1140","Abt 1161":"noin 1161","before 1162":"ennen vuotta 1162","1162":"1162","1140":"1140","of Butley, Cheshire, England":"Butley, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"Abt 1140–":"environ 1140–Décédée","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1162–Male":"1162–Décédé","1140–Female":"1140–Décédée","about 1162":"environ 1162","Abt 1140":"environ 1140","Abt 1161":"environ 1161","befo